column20: Allow me to use it on other devices such as a smartphone

column14: Data storage locations should be more clearly advertised, most people would be unhappy with their data being stored and processed in places like Russia, China, Korea and more recently perhaps even the US. Being able to see and also control where this data is stored would be helpful.

column12: I would say it depends on what options are available to the user. I know on my laptop and phone, I have mine set to lock after an amount of time and then use my biometrics (face or finger print) but on my desktop, I can’t be bothered to always type my password in so I let it be less secure and only lock on restarts.
column14: Less of a concern and more of something I look for in one; being open source and having the ability to self host if I want. Bitwarden is the one I choose for these reasons
That a password manager would be linked/synced to another device used by someone else by mistake

column20: If it was available on all devices
